    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Phonetics / Phonology  ",
          "bold": true,
          "textSize": "heading-one"
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "How humans produce and organize the sounds of their language into an abstract system of phonemes and syllables. ",
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "italic": true
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Basics 101 ",
          "textSize": "heading-two"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "When we speak of the phonetics and phonology of a singing voice, we are talking about the way singers produce linguistic sounds (phonetics) and how those sounds are organized into an abstract system (phonology). That is, phonetics refers to the physical gestures and acoustic signals that make up speech, or what your tongue, lips, and vocal folds are doing to create a sound. Phonology, by contrast, is how those sounds are patterned and interpreted within a language. It is the system that allows listeners to recognize which differences in sound matter and which do not."
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading-three",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading-three",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The IPA (International Phonetic Alphabet)",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "To transcribe and study these sounds, linguists use the "
        },
        {
          "text": "International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": ", a standardized system for representing speech sounds across languages. Each symbol corresponds to a specific sound, regardless of how that sound is spelled in any particular language. For example, the letter < c > in Spanish can be represented with a /k/ in the IPA in words like \""
        },
        {
          "text": "c",
          "italic": true,
          "bold": true,
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": "asas",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "\" or as a /s/ in words like \""
        },
        {
          "text": "pare",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "c",
          "italic": true,
          "bold": true,
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": "er\"",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": ". The IPA provides analysts with a uniform and precise code for indicating the gestures and place of articulation for linguistic sounds independent from the phonological systems in which they are locally organized. "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "https://drive.google.com/file/d/1f2IsRTI1-rk5d1yhXxF4TRpK_VQtwYd4/view?usp=sharing",
      "caption": "IPA Chart (2020) ",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The IPA organizes sounds first according to their "
        },
        {
          "text": "place",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": " or articulation, and then their "
        },
        {
          "text": "manner",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": ". That is, instead of us saying \"an 's' sound,\" we can use a term like \"alveolar fricative\". \"Alveolar\" here is the place of articulation, because the tip of the tongue touches the alveolar ridge to make this sound. \"Fricative\" is the manner of articulation, which is when we allow a stream of high-frequency air to pass through the opening we've created with our tongue placement. In comparison, the sound /k/ is called a \"velar stop,\" because the tongue touches the velum and stops the air for a brief moment. Below is a diagram of the "
        },
        {
          "text": "articulators",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": ", which are the parts of the mouth, nose, and throat/vocal tract used to produce speech sounds. "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "https://drive.google.com/file/d/1rRKMYw9Mwin3GsqZOWn4gcpo77ctvKvI/view?usp=sharing",
      "caption": "Speech Articulators",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Phonemes & Allophones ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "A "
        },
        {
          "text": "phoneme",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": " is an organizing unit that indexes a meaningful contrast in a language. In other words, it is a sound that, if changed, can change the meaning of a word."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "For example, in Spanish /p/ vs /b/ distinguishes the words \""
        },
        {
          "text": "papa",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "\" and \""
        },
        {
          "text": "baba",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "\", or the sounds /b/ and /"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Phonemes are written between slashes: / /"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Basic Atlas Index ",
          "textSize": "heading-two"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Each of the following entries will follow this template to convey the following information: "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "",
          "textSize": "heading-four"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-four",
          "text": "Articulation/Orthographic Representation "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "This section covers how the sound is produced, its phonological environment, and the conventional symbols used for its identification in writing and the IPA"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "In phonetics (the study of how linguistic sound is physically produced), sounds are named by first the place of articulation in the mouth, and second by the manner of articulation. So, an "
        },
        {
          "text": "alveolar",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (place) "
        },
        {
          "text": "fricative",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (manner) is a sound where the tongue touches the alveolar ridge right behind our upper incisors while producing frication, which happens when a lot of very fast-moving air escapes from around the tongue. In English and Spanish, this sound is represented in writing mostly with an < s > and sometimes a < c > (e.g., la"
        },
        {
          "text": "s",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": " "
        },
        {
          "text": "c",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": "inco "
        },
        {
          "text": "s",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": "illa"
        },
        {
          "text": "s",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": "). In the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA), this sound is represented with an /s/. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-four",
          "text": "A brief history "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "This explains the origins of the sound and a dialectal map of its use in the Hispanophone world "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-four",
          "text": "In Puerto Rico"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "This section will explain the allophonic variation in Puerto Rico, including examples of interview speech from reggaetón artists. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-four",
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-four",
          "text": "In Reggaetón "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "This section will exemplify contemporary research on the sound in reggaetón, providing examples from different artists to showcase each claim. "
        }
      ]
